“5 things to remember when starting your fitness journey” 

✅Be patient with yourself 
Being patient when beginning a new journey isn’t always easy. And when you’re waiting for results or improvement, it’s tough to remember that the process takes time. There are no magic formulas or secrets to overnight success. But if you’re patient, disciplined, and committed, your efforts will eventually pay off.

✅Consistency is key! You won’t see the results you want if you aren’t consistent in the gym AND in the kitchen! 

✅Your body is unique, embrace it 
Comparison is definitely the thief of joy! Your body is unique and it may not look the same as anyone else’s but that’s ok it’s not supposed to! It’s uniquely yours ❤️

✅Have a solid workout plan to stick with
Say no to random workouts in the gym! 🚫🙅🏾‍♀️🙅🏾‍♀️Random workouts won’t get you the results you want. You definitely want to be intentional every time you step in the gym 🏋🏾‍♀️

✅Accept feelings of discomfort‼️
When you first start exercising you’ll experience feelings of discomfort such as shortness of breath, sweating and aching muscles after exercising. Don’t worry, this is completely normal and everyone feels like this when they’re first starting out. Keep going!

Here are some common mistakes made when doing Bulgarian split squats:

❌ Excessive Forward lean ❌
It’s tempting and common to lose focus on your
core-particularly your abdominals and spinal
erectors -as you move through the downward
phase of the Bulgarian split squat. Not only does
this forward lean limit the core benefits of the
exercise, but it makes you more likely to place
too much stress on your front knee, shifting your
weight too far forward. (A slight lean is fine.)

❌Rising Onto the Toes/ heel rising ❌
A bad habit that sometimes occurs when your
alignment and form are otherwise poor is to rise
onto the ball and toes of your front foot as you
squat down. This usually indicates one of two
things: 1) your front foot is too close to the
bench, and you need to move it forward to
maintain better balance and alignment, or 2)
you’re leaning forward at your hips as you
perform the squat, and you need to rise onto
your toes to support the forward shift in your weight to remain balanced. 

Try these adjustments and you will see a major difference in your form! Using proper form is crucial to your progress and weight lifting journey!

1. Social Anxiety: Meeting new people can be daunting, especially if you’re naturally shy. This can make it challenging to put yourself out there and initiate conversations. I encourage you to do so! It is so worth it! 

2. Being overly suspicious of people: when you’re overly suspicious, you might misinterpret innocent actions, or words, as evidence of malicious intent. Struggling to shed pounds despite your efforts can be frustrating, but identifying the reasons behind the challenge can help you adjust your approach for better success. Here are some reasons why you might not be losing weight:

Unclear Goals: If your goals are vague or unrealistic, it’s harder to stay motivated and track progress. Define clear, achievable, and specific goals.

Lack of Consistency: Inconsistent efforts can lead to slow progress or setbacks. Consistency is crucial for achieving fitness goals.

Unrealistic Expectations: Expecting rapid results can lead to frustration. Sustainable changes take time.

Inadequate Planning: Not having a structured workout plan or a well-balanced diet can hinder progress.

Improper Nutrition: Poor dietary choices, such as excessive calorie consumption or inadequate protein intake, can affect your progress.

How To overcome these challenges:

1.Set SMART goals (Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Time-bound).
2.Develop a well-rounded fitness plan.
Focus on balanced nutrition.
3.Prioritize sleep and stress management.
Track your progress.
4.Adapt your plan as needed.
5.Seek professional guidance if necessary.

Remember, progress might not always be linear, but consistent effort and adjustments can lead you closer to your fitness aspirations.

The healthiness of alcoholic drinks can vary widely based on their ingredients, alcohol content, and portion sizes. Generally, the most unhealthy alcoholic drinks tend to be those with high sugar content, excessive alcohol levels, and additional unhealthy ingredients. Here are some examples of alcoholic drinks that are often considered among the least healthy:

Sugary Cocktails: Cocktails made with high-sugar mixers, syrups, and liqueurs can be extremely unhealthy. Examples include Piña Colada, Mai Tai, and Long Island Iced Tea. These drinks can pack a significant amount of calories and sugar.

Cream-Based Cocktails: Cocktails that contain heavy cream or dairy products, such as White Russian or Brandy Alexander, can be high in saturated fat and calories.

Dessert Wines: Sweet dessert wines, like Port and Sherry, are known for their high sugar content and can be unhealthy if consumed in large quantities.

High-Alcohol Beer: Some specialty and craft beers can have high alcohol content and can be calorie-dense.

If you choose to consume alcohol, consider opting for drinks with lower sugar content, moderate alcohol levels, and consuming them responsibly. Always prioritize your health and safety when consuming alcoholic beverages.

1. Schedule Workouts Consistently: Create a workout schedule that fits your lifestyle and stick to it as closely as possible. Consistency is key to forming a habit.

2. Set Small, Achievable Targets: Break your big fitness goals into smaller, manageable milestones. Achieving these mini-goals provides a sense of accomplishment and keeps you motivated.

3. Find a strong accountability partner: Partnering up with someone who shares your fitness goals can provide motivation and accountability. You can encourage each other to stay consistent.

4. Prepare Your Gym Bag: Pack your gym bag the night before and have it ready to grab and go! This reduces barriers and excuses for skipping workouts.

5. Track your progress: Keeping track of your progress helps you stay consistent because looking back at your before and after pictures will show you all the work you are putting in put in is working and worth it!

Hey y’all! I’m back with more helpful tips on overeating! We ALL struggle with this from time to time so save this post and come back to it as needed! 

Here are some of the strategies that I use personally!! 

📌Turn off your TV

When the TV is off, you can focus on your meal and be more mindful of what you’re eating. This can lead to better portion control and a greater appreciation of the flavors and textures of your food.

📌Avoid eating from containers

When you eat from containers, it’s more challenging to gauge proper portion sizes. This can lead to overeating, as you may lose track of how much you’ve consumed.

📌Avoiding last-minute food choices

Making last-minute meal and snack choices is a common trigger for overeating. When people make impulsive food decisions, it can be easy to pick nutritionally poor, calorie-dense foods.

📌Incorporate natural appetite suppressants

If you’re wondering how to stop overeating, suppressants can help! NATURAL appetite suppressants that is! ☺️

include high-fiber foods like chia seeds and legumes, hot spices like cayenne and turmeric, and grapefruit essential oil, which helps curb cravings. These all-natural, fat-burning foods help keep you from overeating without the health risks that come with traditional suppressants.

If you struggle with late night snacking Choosing healthy snacks to combat post-dinner hunger can help you satisfy your cravings without derailing your weight loss journey! 

Eating a small, healthy snack in the evening can curb late-night cravings and reduce the likelihood of overindulging during late-night binges.

Remember that portion control is key when snacking, especially in the evening. Try to choose snacks that are balanced in macronutrients, incorporating protein, fiber, and healthy fats, as these components can help you feel full and satisfied until your next meal.
